---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Eyebrow from "../components/Eyebrow.astro";
---
<Base title="How it works">
  <section class="max-w-wide mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 pt-14 md:pt-20 pb-10">
    <Eyebrow label="Method" index="Ch. II" />
    <h1 class="font-display font-medium text-ink leading-[1.05] text-[2.6rem] md:text-[3.8rem] mt-5 max-w-4xl">
      A pipeline, not a script.
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-5 max-w-prose text-[1.08rem] leading-[1.7] text-ink">
      Most retail traders test strategies with a spreadsheet or a one-off Python script. That
      process leaks lookahead bias, invites overfitting, and ignores frictions. The framework is
      an opinionated harness that forces an honest answer to a single question.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr class="hairline" />

  <section class="max-w-wide mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-14">
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <header class="md:col-span-4">
        <Eyebrow label="The five stages" index="01" />
        <h2 class="font-display text-[2rem] md:text-[2.3rem] mt-3 leading-[1.12]">
          Strategy in, scorecard out.
        </h2>
      </header>
      <div class="md:col-span-8">
        <ol class="space-y-0">
          {[
            {
              n: "01",
              t: "Strategy interface",
              b: "Every strategy subclasses the same Strategy base class. Signal mode returns BUY / SELL / HOLD per bar; target-position mode specifies exact sizes (including shorts and partials). The framework takes care of sizing, execution, and reporting from there.",
            },
            {
              n: "02",
              t: "Data layer",
              b: "Equities via Yahoo, Alpaca, Polygon, Tiingo, and more. Crypto via CCXT (110+ exchanges, public OHLCV without API keys). Options via synthetic Black-Scholes or the free philippdubach chains dataset back to 2008.",
            },
            {
              n: "03",
              t: "Dual execution engines",
              b: "Every run executes twice. The bar engine replays daily OHLCV with market orders at next open. The event engine replays the same bars as order-book events, filling stop / limit / OCO intrabar. If the PnL diverges, the strategy is execution-sensitive.",
            },
            {
              n: "04",
              t: "Monte Carlo stressors",
              b: "Six generators run automatically: geometric Brownian motion (sanity baseline), block bootstrap, Markov regime switching, noise injection, Heston stochastic volatility, and a trained cGAN conditioned on four real SPY regimes.",
            },
            {
              n: "05",
              t: "Standardized scorecard",
              b: "A four-page PNG: equity curve and trade stats; Monte Carlo distributions; bar-vs-event comparison; letter grades across performance, risk, trade quality, and robustness. Same output format for every strategy, every member, every semester.",
            },
          ].map((s, i) => (
            <li class={`py-6 ${i !== 0 ? "border-t border-hair" : ""}`}>
              <div class="grid grid-cols-[auto_1fr] gap-5">
                <div class="font-mono text-[0.82rem] tracking-[0.08em] text-primary pt-1">{s.n}</div>
                <div>
                  <h3 class="font-display text-2xl md:text-[1.7rem] leading-tight text-ink">{s.t}</h3>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-[1rem] leading-[1.65] text-ink">{s.b}</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="double-rule" />

  <!-- BAR VS EVENT -->
  <section class="max-w-wide mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-14">
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <header class="md:col-span-4">
        <Eyebrow label="The divergence test" index="02" />
        <h2 class="font-display text-[2rem] md:text-[2.3rem] mt-3 leading-[1.1]">
          Bar vs. event, side by side.
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-[0.98rem] leading-[1.65] text-ink max-w-sm">
          The part most non-quant audiences don't see. Two engines exist because stop orders can
          fire intrabar and bar engines can't model that. Running both and measuring the gap is
          the cheapest form of robustness check.
        </p>
      </header>
      <div class="md:col-span-8 grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div class="border border-hair bg-white p-5">
          <div class="font-mono text-[0.68rem] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Engine A</div>
          <h3 class="font-display text-xl text-ink mt-1">Bar-based</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-[0.95rem] leading-[1.6] text-ink">
            Replays daily OHLCV. Every order becomes &ldquo;buy at tomorrow's open.&rdquo; Fast,
            simple, sufficient for swing and position strategies &mdash; but fundamentally cannot
            model a stop-loss triggering intraday.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border border-hair bg-white p-5">
          <div class="font-mono text-[0.68rem] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Engine B</div>
          <h3 class="font-display text-xl text-ink mt-1">Event-driven</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-[0.95rem] leading-[1.6] text-ink">
            Replays the same bars as order-book events. Stop orders fire intrabar at the trigger
            price. Bracket exits (OCO stop-loss plus take-profit) are real. Captures what the bar
            engine cannot.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="hairline" />

  <!-- QUOTE -->
  <section class="max-w-wide mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-14 md:py-20">
    <blockquote class="font-display italic text-[1.6rem] md:text-[2rem] leading-[1.25] text-ink max-w-3xl">
      &ldquo;If a strategy performs well on one data source but poorly on another, that's a red flag
      &mdash; the strategy might be fitting to quirks in the data rather than real market dynamics.&rdquo;
    </blockquote>
    <div class="mt-4 font-mono text-[0.72rem] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">
      — roles.md &nbsp;·&nbsp; Data Layer section
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="hairline" />

  <section class="max-w-wide mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <header class="md:col-span-4">
        <Eyebrow label="The bar" index="03" />
        <h2 class="font-display text-[2rem] md:text-[2.3rem] mt-3 leading-[1.12]">
          If the scorecard says it works, it works.
        </h2>
      </header>
      <div class="md:col-span-8 max-w-prose text-[1rem] leading-[1.7] text-ink space-y-4">
        <p>
          A strategy that earns a pass on this scorecard has cleared a deliberately high bar:
          positive returns against a benchmark, a negative Sharpe on pure GBM noise, survivable
          drawdowns across GAN-generated crash regimes, and agreement between two independent
          execution engines. That combination is hard to fake.
        </p>
        <p>
          Nothing else is needed to decide whether a strategy is worth trading. The scorecard is
          the answer, not a waypoint toward one.
        </p>
        <p class="italic text-muted">
          See <a href="/limitations" class="primary">Limitations</a> for an honest audit of what
          this framework is and isn't.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
